<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-183-212 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 537 049</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 3 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Satellite firm raises $100 million. (American Mobile SatelliteCorp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Mobile Satellite Corp. (Finance).andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionLegal IssuesGovernment AgencyLicensingCourt CasesFinancingSatellite Communications.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>SATELLITE FIRM RAISES $100 MILLION 04/03/91 WASHINGTON, D.C., U.S.A., 1991APR 3 (NB) -- American Mobile Satellite Corporation announced that $100million of additional equity financing has been committed by existingshareholders, bringing the total committed equity to $140 million.andP;  AMSC'sownership will reflect three major shareholders -- Hughes Communications,McCaw Cellular/LIN Broadcasting, and Mtel - each with over 25 percent.andP;  Theother shareholders are Mobile Satellite, North American Mobile Satellite, andSkylink.andM;Completing the funding was important because of a recent Court of Appealsdecision remanding its license back to the Federal Communications Commission.andO;The FCC is taking back the case after three firms, which were rejected forthe license, sued.andP;  The license was awarded to the consortium in 1989.andO;Spokesman Ruth Pritchard admits, &quot;There is a cloud now over the license&quot; but&quot;We're operating under the assumption of business as usual until we hearotherwise.&quot; Analysts speculate that ownership of the license may be adjustedin some minor way, by negotiation, as a result of the Court of Appealsaction.andM;AMSC is proceeding with the construction of its first satellite, cooperatingwith Telesat Mobile of Canada, to develop a North American regional mobilesatellite system.andP;  Each company's satellite will back up the other, andsupport comparable services.andP;  AMSC is also working with the NationalAeronautics and Space Administration to finalize an agreement under whichAMSC will provide satellite services to federal, state and local governmentusers, in exchange for NASA's equivalent support in launch services.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19910402/Press Contact: Ruth Pritchard-Kelly, AmericanMobile Satellite Corporation, 202-872-7657)</TEXT></DOC>